<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-06-07T01:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-06-07T01:00:00-05:00" n="656" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d656">
                    <note rend="inline" type="source">500.A15A5/884: Telegram</note>
                    <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Grew</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                    <opener>
                        <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-06-07T15:00:00+09:00">June 7, 1937—3
                            p.m.</date><lb/>[Received June 7—4:10 a.m.]</dateline>
                    </opener>
                    <p>152. Department’s 75, June 4, 8 p.m.<note n="23" xml:id="d656fn23">See
                            footnote 22, <ref target="#pg_630">p. 630</ref>.</note> The question of
                        gun calibers was taken up today in my initial interview with the new Foreign
                            Minister<note n="24" xml:id="d656fn24">K. Hirota.</note> and an <hi rend="italic">aide-mémoire</hi> left with him embodying all the points
                            <pb facs="0644" n="632" xml:id="pg_632"/> set forth by the Department. I
                        said that my Government would appreciate receiving a reply before the 21st
                        of this month. Hirota made no comment except that he would have to refer the
                        matter to the Navy Ministry.</p>
                    <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi></signed></closer>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>